<br>
I guess I'm confused about what your alternative to the whole mess would have been. You don't approve of taking Saddam out by force. You don't approve of lifting the sanctions while Saddam was in power. Were you kind of hoping that Saddam would just magically disappear, or were you satisfied leaving the sanctions in place and letting Saddam continue as he was? The sanctions inflicted terrible misery, I wouldn't support any idea that allowed them to continue.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It would be more credible if we were truly trying to change the world; this noble &quot;we got an evil person out of power&quot; stuff might hold up if we approached other people similar to Saddam.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
What the hell? I'm not trying to be noble, I'm trying to be practical. Saddam hated us, and, left alone -- and this is what makes him unique for the most part, at least it distinguishes him from some warlord in Africa -- could and would undoubtedly have developed and distributed sophisticated WMD in ways harmful to us. The only reason he didn't was because we contained him. But containment, ultimately, wasn't the answer, it was going on too long and at too much cost to the Iraqi people. So we did what we should have done 12 years ago, went in and took him out. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Saying &quot;we did it for the good of the Iraqi people!&quot; doesn't hold much weight when we can turn a blind eye to the Liberian people.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Bullshit. If I give one homeless guy on the street five bucks, it doesn't mean I have some secret motive because I didn't also give five bucks to homeless guy number two. What you said doesn't make sense. Nor am I turning a blind eye; I myself posted an article on this board a few weeks back about horrible shit that was happening in Africa, and I support those in the UN who say that we need to send more peacekeeping forces to Africa to enforce a very much needed peace. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Shooting civilians at anti-American rallies doesn't do too too much when you're trying to raise Iraqi public opinion.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
People fuck up. What do you want me to say, that killing civilians is a bad idea? I agree. I don't understand how that affects anything else. This whole endeavour is a messy business, but, again, a hell of a lot better than leaving Saddam or the sanctions in place. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yes, Saddam probably would have killed more, but I really don't think we should be judging ourselves in terms of &quot;hey, we're better than Saddam!&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think this is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>exactly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> how we should be judging ourselves. How do you think we should be judging ourselves? We killed 4000 civilians. You admit it's likely Saddam would have killed more, let's say 5000. Are you saying we shouldn't have invaded unless we know for sure we won't kill more than, say, 3000 civilians, even though we know the cost of inaction will be much higher? You've honestly lost me here.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>No, I'm not making that up. So much for magnamity.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This situation was fucked up from day one. Either way, people were going to die. There is such a thing as the lesser of two evils being the superior choice, even if it's still an evil.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You seem to be under the impression that not only did Iraqis not know about these torture chambers, but that we'd be better for the Iraqis than any attempts at government they can set up in the short term. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
They probably did know about the chambers. I was trying to make a point. And I don't recall ever saying that we know better than the Iraqis how they should govern themselves. In fact, you may recall a very long thread a couple months back where I argued with Grimstaff and Torcer for like five or ten pages, that we need to include the Iraqis at every single step of this process and get the hell out of there as soon as we can after making sure the new government won't immediately start persecuting people en masse or collapse on itself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I really don't think people in the Middle East buy that we're doing this purely of our own magnamity; we have our own interests involved here.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
We do have our own interests here. Greater stability and safety in the region and, by extension, the rest of the world.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>b) You must not have read his posts, because almost every time he was confronted with a question he didn't have an immediate answer for, the response was &quot;just wait and see, everything's going to turn out fine&quot;. In fact, that's the kind of crap which led to his &quot;Still Waiting&quot; post, and hence this post.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Did I say Grimstaff wasn't a dick? He is a dick. But as for &quot;just wait and see, everything's going to turn out fine&quot;, if I recall, he usually uses that line when people try to stay stuff like &quot;It's been two months three weeks five days and three seconds since we took Baghdad why are we still there we're never leaving and the Iraqis will all turn into terrorists because of it wtf&quot;. This is a long-term effort, our government has said that all along.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Most of the 3rd Infantry was supposed to be back home by now, but their stay has been extended indefinitely. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I know. My wife's cousin's husband is a chemical specialist for the 3rd, his wife got an email the other day that said they won't be coming home until the end of the summer at the earliest. Nobody's happy about that. If we're still there in a year or so screwing around, I'll be right here on this board bitching about it with you. But none of that changes the fact that we'd have to be pretty goddamn awful in order to come close to the misery of Saddam+sanctions. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=valtser>Valtser</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice... forever!</span><br>  Posts: 391<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/18/03 4:09 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Grimstaff, now I'M waiting</span><hr size=1> Damn you people. Iraq is so last month. Fuck Iraq, Fuck Saddam, Fuck everything over there. Why not just pay attention to whats going on with our lives and not the world? <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page  <b>1</b> <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=2280.topic&start=21&stop=40>2</a><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=2280.topic&start=41&stop=60>3</a><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=2280.topic&start=61&stop=80>4</a><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=2280.topic&start=81&stop=100>5</a><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=2280.topic&start=101&stop=110>6</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilati